@Dave K.

Without some knowledge of astrology much of the history of  art, literature, science, and  Western Civilization cannot be properly interpreted.

Astrological factors governed the practice of medicine well into modern times.  The sun and moon rule the seasons and the tides.  Many gardeners still swear by the old sayings of when to plant and harvest crops.

@Al  in Pittsburgh

Your "astrological factors" are astronomy, not astrology. Tides, seasons, when/where the sun and moon are in the sky, knowing when planting season starts - these are all astronomy.

Knowing the difference between science and utter nonsense is important.

@Dave K.

Since you're a fan of science, "The Human Cosmos" by Jo Marchant is an incredible book about how astrological observations in ancient times led to astronomical observations throughout history and into the present--and the frontiers of human understanding that's still exist.

I'm a chemical engineer with a PhD, but the history can be fun to think about, and informs my understanding of art and literature.  And I notice whenever I get a personality/work-style test at work, the personality types often map exactly onto the astrological signs.  Humans have been saying the same thing in different ways for a long time.

@Le Biscuit à Soupe

Nah, this didn’t require knowledge of arcana/trivia — but it did include some entries that, for solvers lacking such knowledge (🙋‍♂️), required heavy usage of crosses, along with a bit of reasoning to fill in the last square or two.

An example from that last category: the “E” in EPT. Oof!

